history.content:
CS 160 is a deceptively easy class. Conceptually the class is very easy; however, the projects are an absolute killer. They sucked up a LOT of my time the semester I took it, and in retrospect, I don't think taking that class was a smart choice. 

EE 120 isn't too bad. Not too difficult conceptually and also not that heavy of a workload.

children.subject: FYI, even though it says 120 is a prereq for robotics, it isn't (it honestly needs to be updated). I took EE106A&B and only a handful of signals stuff comes in useful for 106B which EE16A/B should cover decently well enough.
Would I be able to register for 106A/B without having taken 120? What's the workload of 106A like? Would I die if I took it with CS160?

I'm pretty sure you can. I had a friend in ME take 106B with me and signed up for it without any difficulties. And for workload of 106A, just search around piazza or under EE125 for it cause I'm pretty sure i might have answered it somewhere else.

I love interfaces, and spent hours working on them for my high school robotics team, so I definitely want to take 160. That being said,  the only reason I am taking 120 is because it's a prerequisite for the robotics classes. I liked EE16A/B ok, but it wasn't anything to get excited about. 

Why was taking 160 not a smart choice for you?

history.content: I know CS160, as a project based class, is very work intensive. How likely am I to die if I take it along side EE120, with a humanities and possibly PE class? I also work part time, 15-20 hours a week, and I really don't want to kill myself or my GPA. How feasible is this?
history.subject: EE120 + CS160 and humanities.
